Container	A lightweight package containing an application and its dependencies.
Image	A template used to create containers.
Docker	Container engine that builds and runs containers using a daemon.
Podman	Docker alternative that is daemonless and supports rootless containers.
Docker Compose	Runs multiple containers on one machine using a YAML file.
Docker Swarm	Docker's built-in orchestration platform for multiple machines.
Kubernetes (K8s)	Container orchestration platform that manages containers across many servers.
k3s	Lightweight Kubernetes distribution for small clusters and edge devices.
OpenShift	Red Hat's enterprise Kubernetes platform with extra tools and security.
Managed Kubernetes	Kubernetes managed by a cloud provider (EKS, AKS, GKE).
Pod	The smallest Kubernetes object; contains one or more containers.
Deployment	Manages Pods and supports scaling, updates, and rollbacks.
ReplicaSet	Ensures the desired number of Pods are running.
Service	Provides a stable IP and DNS name for Pods.
ClusterIP	Internal Service accessible only within the cluster.
NodePort	Exposes a Service through a port on every node.
LoadBalancer	Exposes a Service using a cloud load balancer.
Headless Service	Gives direct access to individual Pods instead of one virtual IP.
StatefulSet	Manages stateful applications with stable names and storage.
DaemonSet	Runs exactly one Pod on every node.
Job	Runs a task once until it completes successfully.
CronJob	Runs Jobs on a schedule (like Linux cron).
Namespace	A logical partition of a Kubernetes cluster.
Label	A key-value pair used to organize Kubernetes objects.
Selector	Finds objects based on matching labels.
NodeSelector	Forces Pods to run only on nodes with specific labels.
ConfigMap	Stores non-sensitive configuration data.
Secret	Stores sensitive data such as passwords or certificates.
Persistent Volume (PV)	The actual storage resource in Kubernetes.
Persistent Volume Claim (PVC)	A request for storage made by a Pod.
StorageClass	Defines the type of storage to provision.
CSI (Container Storage Interface)	Standard interface between Kubernetes and storage providers.
Volume	Storage mounted inside a Pod.
emptyDir	Temporary shared storage that exists while the Pod runs.
Init Container	Runs before the main container to perform setup tasks.
Sidecar Container	Extra container in the same Pod providing helper functionality (logging, proxy, etc.).
Rolling Update	Gradually replaces old Pods with new ones without downtime.
Rollback	Restores the previous application version after a failed update.
RollingUpdate Strategy	Updates Pods gradually while keeping the application available.
Recreate Strategy	Deletes all old Pods before creating new ones, causing downtime.
Liveness Probe	Checks if an application is alive; restarts it if necessary.
Readiness Probe	Checks if an application is ready to receive traffic.
Startup Probe	Gives slow-starting applications extra time before health checks begin.
Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA)	Automatically changes the number of Pods based on load.
Cluster Autoscaler	Automatically adds or removes cluster nodes.
CNI (Container Network Interface)	Plugin that provides networking for Kubernetes Pods.
Ingress	Routes external HTTP/HTTPS traffic into the cluster.
Route (OpenShift)	OpenShift's version of Ingress for exposing applications.
ImagePullSecret	Secret used to authenticate to private container registries.
YAML Manifest	Configuration file describing Kubernetes resources.
kubectl	Command-line tool used to manage Kubernetes clusters.
Podman CLI	Command-line tool used to manage Podman containers.
Containerfile/Dockerfile	File describing how to build a container image.
FROM	Specifies the base image.
RUN	Executes commands during image build.
COPY	Copies files into the image.
WORKDIR	Sets the working directory inside the image.
CMD	Default command executed when the container starts.
ENTRYPOINT	Defines the main executable of the container.
EXPOSE	Documents which port the application listens on (does not publish it).
ENV	Defines environment variables inside the image.
USER	Specifies which Linux user runs the container.
Daemon	Background process managing containers (e.g., Docker's dockerd).
Daemonless	No background daemon required (Podman).
Rootless	Runs containers without root privileges for better security.
Microservices	Application split into many small independent services.
Monolith	Application built as one large program.
Orchestration	Automated management of container deployment, scaling, networking, and recovery.
CI/CD	Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment pipeline for automated software delivery.
S2I (Source-to-Image)	OpenShift feature that builds container images directly from source code.
Operator	Kubernetes extension that automates management of complex applications.
CRD (Custom Resource Definition)	Lets Kubernetes support custom resource types.
Vendor Lock-in	Dependence on one vendor's technology, making migration harder.
Autoscaling	Automatically adjusts resources according to demand.
High Availability (HA)	System remains available even if some components fail.
Resilience	Ability to recover automatically from failures.
Stateful Application	Application that stores persistent data (e.g., databases).
Stateless Application	Application that stores no persistent state (e.g., web server).
Rolling Restart	Restart Pods gradually without downtime.
OOMKilled	Container killed because it exceeded its memory limit.
CrashLoopBackOff	Container repeatedly crashes and Kubernetes delays restarts.
ImagePullBackOff	Kubernetes cannot download the container image.
Pending	Pod cannot be scheduled yet (insufficient resources, missing PVC, wrong nodeSelector, etc.).
Completed	Container finished successfully and exited normally.
Terminating	Pod is shutting down but has not been fully removed yet.
